eople want to play with it.<br />&gt;<br />&gt; Doesn't even look all that hacky to me. Any hack in it that I didn't<br />&gt; notice? :-)<br /><br />The code to use asm goto sadly doesn't have any fallback at all for<br />the "no asm goto available".<br /><br />I guess we're getting close to "we require asm goto support", but I<br />don't think we're there yet.<br /><br />Also, while "unsafe_put_user()" has been converted to use asm goto<br />(and yes, it really does generate much nicer code), the same is not<br />true of "unsafe_get_user()". Because sadly, gcc does not support asm<br />goto with output values.<br /><br />So, realistically, my patch is not _technically_ hacky, but it's<br />simply not viable as things stand, and it's more of a tech<br />demonstration than anything else.<br /><br />               Linus<br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
